@remark *********************************************************************

@node IntroductionNode "ScreenBacker: Introduction"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenBacker adds backdrop patterns and customized menus to public
screens. It doesn't have a window with gadgets; instead, it is an
ARexx host and you can only talk to it via the ARexx language.@{par}

You already have ARexx installed on your Amiga; although originally a
separate, commercial product, ARexx was so useful that Commodore (in a
rare fit of wisdom) included it in Workbench Release 2 and above.@{par}

Unfortunately, in a more typical penny-pinching exercise, C= didn't
supply an ARexx manual with the budget model Amigas. If you don't have
an ARexx manual, you can get a very comprehensive (if a bit technical)
guide to it as ARexxGuide in the util/rexx directory of AmiNet, or
from your favourite PD supplier. This is a document in AmigaGuide
format which you can read using AmigaGuide (WB2) or MultiView (WB3).
In addition, several popular Amiga magazines have run ARexx tutorials.@{par}

Using ARexx you can perform all the usual computation-like activities
normal in any programming language, but in addition, you can control
other applications that have an ARexx port, including ScreenBacker.@{par}

If this all sounds a bit heavy, you might prefer to use a graphical
(windows and gadgets) interface to ScreenBacker - have a look at the
@{"ScreenMaster User Guide" link "ScreenMaster.guide/Main"} instead.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node RequirementsNode "ScreenBacker: Requirements"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenBacker requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} AmigaOS 2.04 / Kickstart V37 or higher.@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} ARexxMast to be running. @{i}(inter-process communication)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The following disk-based Commodore libraries are required, but are
part of AmigaOS 2.04 (and later releases) anyway:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} rexxsyslib.library V36 or higher. @{i}(ARexx support)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} commodities.library V37 or higher. @{i}(commodity support)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} asl.library V37 or higher. @{i}(requesters)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

Additionally, ScreenBacker will use the ReqTools library (V38 or
higher) for its requesters, if it is available.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node TooltypesNode "ScreenBacker: Tooltypes and Shell Arguments"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Tooltypes and Shell Arguments@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

The tooltypes ScreenBacker looks for in its program icon are described
below. The arguments used from a Shell are identical, except where
stated otherwise. The full Shell template (with abbreviations) is:

@{code}
                   MA=MASTER/K, PR=CX_PRIORITY/K/N,
               LA=LANGUAGE/K, FL=FLUSH/S, RI=READICON/S
@{body}

ScreenBacker's tooltypes consist of three kinds:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{b}String@{ub} - You must supply a string of some kind; a filename,
public screen name, etc. For example, "LANGUAGE=deutsch".@{par}

@{b}Integer@{ub} - You must supply a numeric value (a whole number).
For example, "CX_PRIORITY=5".@{par}

@{b}Boolean@{ub} - In tooltypes you must supply one of the following: YES, NO,
TRUE or FALSE. For example, "FLUSH=YES". You can also omit the value
entirely, which indicates the YES or TRUE state. On a Shell command
line, just state the keyword without a value to get the TRUE state,
omit the keyword for FALSE.@{par}
@{lindent 0}

@{code}
    Tooltype         Type     Short Description
    ------------     ----     --------------------------------------
    @{"MASTER     " link MASTERNode     }     STR      Location of ScreenMaster program.
    @{"CX_PRIORITY" link CX_PRIORITYNode}     INT      Priority of hotkey among commodities.
    @{"LANGUAGE   " link LANGUAGENode   }     STR      Specify language catalog.
    @{"FLUSH      " link FLUSHNode      }     BOOL     Quit when last backdrop closed.
    @{"READICON   " link READICONNode   }     BOOL     Read config. from tooltypes (Shell).
@{body}

If you put ScreenBacker in your WBStartUp drawer, you should add the
tooltype "DONOTWAIT" so Workbench won't wait for ScreenBacker to quit
before continuing with its start up.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MASTERNode "ScreenBacker: MASTER Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}MASTER Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      String
Default:   ScreenMaster
Shell:     MA=MASTER/K
Tooltype:  MASTER
@{body}

When you pick the "Show Interface" item from the @{"standard menu" link StdMenuNode}
attached by ScreenBacker to a public screen, ScreenBacker tries to
open the ScreenMaster program, launching it if it is not already
running. If ScreenMaster is in ScreenBacker's search path this will
work, otherwise use this tooltype to tell ScreenBacker where to find
it.@{par}

I recommend you add the READICON keyword as well, so that
ScreenMaster, when started, reads its configuration from its
tooltypes. For example: "MASTER=Work:Things/ScreenMaster READICON".@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CX_PRIORITYNode "ScreenBacker: CX_PRIORITY Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CX_PRIORITY Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      Integer
Default:   0
Shell:     PR=CX_PRIORITY/K/N
Tooltype:  CX_PRIORITY
@{body}

Use this tooltype to set ScreenBacker's priority relative to the other
commodities running. Normally there is no need to change this.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node LANGUAGENode "ScreenBacker: LANGUAGE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}LANGUAGE Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      String
Default:   <system default>
Shell:     LA=LANGUAGE/K
Tooltype:  LANGUAGE
@{body}

ScreenBacker supports the locale library of AmigaOS 2.1 and above,
allowing it to display text and messages in your preferred language.
You would normally specify the language with the Locale Preferences
program; this tooltype allows you to override that setting if
necessary.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node FLUSHNode "ScreenBacker: FLUSH Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}FLUSH Keyword@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     FL=FLUSH/S
Tooltype:  FLUSH
@{body}

If you set the FLUSH option to TRUE, ScreenBacker will quit as soon as
the last backdrop or menu it has open closes.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node READICONNode "ScreenBacker: READICON Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}READICON@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     RI=READICON/S
Tooltype:  <not applicable>
@{body}

This keyword is only available from the Shell command line. It makes
ScreenBacker read its configuration from its icon's tooltypes rather
than the command line. This is useful in conjunction with program
launchers that run programs as if from a Shell. Ordinarily you would
have to duplicate all your preferred ScreenBacker configuration
arguments in the command that you supply to the launcher, but by
specifying READICON, you can keep your settings in the icon.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CommandsNode "ScreenBacker: ARexx Commands"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}ARexx Commands@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenBacker's ARexx port is called, appropriately enough,
'SCREENBACKER'.@{par}

Multiple commands on a single line are legal, and are evaluated in the
order they appear below. So if you supply, for example, "OPEN=PubScr
CLOSE=OtherScr", a default menu will be attached to PubScr, and any
backdrop or menu on OtherScr will be removed.@{par}

Failure to complete a command results in a requester being displayed
with an appropriate error message, unless the @{"SILENT" link SILENTCmdNode} keyword is
supplied.@{par}

All the commands return a primary result code, available in the ARexx
variable RC, but no secondary result (RESULT variable). Errors during
the processing of a command (such as an invalid value for a keyword)
return RC_FATAL (20). Errors that occur while carrying out the command
(such as being unable to open a backdrop) return RC_ERROR (10).
Finally, errors such as not being able to find a named public screen
(for example, CLOSE "NoScreenWithThisName") return RC_WARN (5).@{par}

No further commands on a given line are processed after an RC_FATAL or
RC_ERROR condition occurs. RC_WARN does @{b}not@{ub} stop further processing.@{par}

Remember that ARexx tends to capitalize everything, so quote public
screen names, which are case sensitive. Also quote any names with
embedded spaces. This includes filenames. The commands themselves are
case-insensitive.@{par}

ScreenBacker understands the following commands:@{par}
@{code}
  @{"OPEN        " link OPENCmdNode  }      Opens a new backdrop or menu.
  @{"CLOSE       " link CLOSECmdNode }      Closes a backdrop or menu.
  @{"SILENT      " link SILENTCmdNode}      A switch to suppress error requesters.
  @{"QUIT        " link QUITCmdNode  }      Quits ScreenBacker, if possible.
  @{"KILL        " link KILLCmdNode  }      Closes all backdrops/menus and quits.
@{body}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node OPENCmdNode "ScreenBacker: OPEN Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}OPEN Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: OP=OPEN/K,PN=PATTERN/K,PC=PATCENTRE/S,PT=PATTILE/S,
          ME=MENU/K,NM=NOMENU/S

Returns:  10 if backdrop couldn't be opened.
           5 if backdrop already present on that screen.
           0 if backdrop opened ok.
@{body}

The OPEN keyword must be followed by the name of the public screen to
attach a backdrop or menu to. You can then specify none or more of the
other options. If you don't add any of the options below, the screen
will simply get a @{"standard menu" link StdMenuNode} attached to it, containing a few
useful public screen management functions.@{par}


@{fg shine}PATTERN <patfile>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-----------------@{fg text}@{par}

Specifies the name of an IFF ILBM or Workbench Preferences pattern
file to apply as a backdrop pattern to this public screen.@{par}

ScreenBacker doesn't currently do any pen remapping, so you should
make sure the screen's palette is suitable for the backdrop. Also, if
given a Workbench 3 pattern preferences file, ScreenBacker will
currently only use the screen pattern recorded in it (ie. not the
Workbench window or drawer window patterns).@{par}


@{fg shine}PATCENTRE@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{par}

If you want the backdrop pattern specified by PATTERN to be centred in
the middle of the screen, supply this switch. Unless you specify the
NOMENU option as well, the screen will get at least the standard menu
attached to it, as well.@{par}


@{fg shine}PATTILE@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{par}

If you want the backdrop pattern specified by PATTERN to be repeated
across and down the screen, supply this switch.@{par}


@{fg shine}MENU <menufile>@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------------@{fg text}@{par}

If you would like to add a @{"custom menu definition" link MenuDefNode} to the public
screen, supply its filename with the MENU keyword. This option is
mutually exclusive with the NOMENU keyword.@{par}


@{fg shine}NOMENU@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{par}

With this switch you can suppress the attachment of a menu to the
screen; use it if you just want to add a backdrop pattern. This option
is mutually exclusive with the MENU keyword, and if you use it, you
must specify a backdrop pattern with the PATTERN keyword.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CLOSECmdNode "ScreenBacker: CLOSE Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CLOSE Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: CL=CLOSE/K

Returns:  5 if screen could not be found, or no backdrop open on it.
          0 if backdrop was closed.
@{body}

Closes the backdrop and/or menu attached to the named public screen.
If the FLUSH switch was specified when ScreenBacker was launched, and
ScreenBacker no longer has any backdrops open, the program will quit.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node SILENTCmdNode "ScreenBacker: SILENT Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}SILENT Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: SI=SILENT/S

Returns:  N/A
@{body}

This is a switch; when SILENT is specified with any other command, it
suppresses any requester that might appear to indicate an error. A
primary result code, in ARexx variable RC, is still returned.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node QUITCmdNode "ScreenBacker: QUIT Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}QUIT Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: QU=QUIT/S

Returns:  10 if ScreenBacker is still has any backdrops open.
           0 if ScreenBacker quit.
@{body}

This switch makes ScreenBacker quit, as long as it doesn't have any
backdrops or menus open.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node KILLCmdNode "ScreenBacker: KILL Command"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}KILL Command@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Template: KILL/S

Returns:  0 always.
@{body}

This switch makes ScreenBacker close all backdrops and menus and quit.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node StdMenuNode "ScreenBacker: The Standard Menu"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}The Standard Menu@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

The standard menu, titled "Project", that ScreenBacker attaches to a
public screen contains the following items:@{par}


@{fg shine}Open Interface@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------------@{fg text}@{par}

Opens the ScreenMaster program, launching it if it is not already
running.@{par}


@{fg shine}Make Default@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------------@{fg text}@{par}

Makes this public screen the system default.@{par}


@{fg shine}Set Palette...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------------@{fg text}@{par}

Opens a palette requester, for adjusting this screen's colours.@{par}


@{fg shine}Load Palette...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------------@{fg text}@{par}

Loads a new palette from a file, either an IFF ILBM or Workbench
Preferences file. A requester is opened to let you choose the file.@{par}


@{fg shine}Save Palette...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------------@{fg text}@{par}

Saves the screen's palette as an IFF ILBM file. A requester is opened
to let you choose the filename.@{par}


@{fg shine}About...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{par}

Displays some information about ScreenBacker.@{par}


@{fg shine}Close Backdrop@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------------@{fg text}@{par}

Closes the backdrop and menu attached to this screen. If the @{"FLUSH" link FLUSHNode}
option was specified when ScreenBacker was launched, and no more
backdrops or menus are open, ScreenBacker will quit.@{par}


@{fg shine}Close Screen@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------------@{fg text}@{par}

Closes the backdrop and menu attached to this screen, and then
instructs ScreenDaemon to close the screen itself. This will fail if
there are any visitor windows open on the screen. If the @{"FLUSH" link FLUSHNode} option
was specified when ScreenBacker was launched, and no more backdrops or
menus are open, ScreenBacker will quit.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MenuDefNode "ScreenBacker: Menu Definition Files"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Menu Definition Files@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=====================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Unless suppressed with the @{"NOMENU" link OPENCmdNode} switch, ScreenBacker adds a small,
@{"standard menu" link StdMenuNode} to public screens. You can extend this menu with items
that launch your favourite programs, like the Workbench Tools menu. To
do this, supply the @{"MENU" link OPENCmdNode} keyword and the name of a menu definition
file. I recommend you use the @{"ScreenMenuEd" link "ScreenMenuEd.guide/Main"} program to create these,
but you don't have to: they are plain text (ASCII) files that can be
created and edited with a text editor.@{par}

A menu definition file consists of a series of records, one per line,
that define consecutive menu titles, item separator bars and menu
items. The definition starts with the second menu title (the first
being that of the standard menu) and proceeds down with new items and
to the right with new menu titles. Each line is parsed with the
following template:@{par}
@{code}
             MENU/K, BAR/S, ITEM/K, CMD=COMMAND/K, KEY/K,
       ST=STACK/K/N, PRI=PRIORITY/K/N, OP=OUTPUT/K, CD=CURDIR/K
@{body}

@{fg shine}MENU/K@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{par}

Start a new menu with the MENU keyword, followed by the desired title.
Enclose the title in quotes if it contains embedded spaces. Naturally,
the first record of the file must be a MENU definition, and the last
record of the file cannot be a MENU definition. No other keywords are
allowed in the record if MENU is used.@{par}


@{fg shine}BAR/S@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-----@{fg text}@{par}

The BAR keyword identifies a separator item. A BAR record must be
preceeded and followed by an ITEM record. No other keywords are
allowed in the record if BAR is used.@{par}


@{fg shine}ITEM/K@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{par}

Define a new item for the current menu with the ITEM keyword, with the
text you want displayed in the menu for that item. Enclose the text in
quotes if it contains embedded spaces. Use the other option keywords
in an ITEM record to specify the command you want executed when that
item is selected:@{par}

@{b}CMD=COMMAND/K@{ub}@{line}
This argument is required and should be the name of the program to
launch - this will be run asynchronously, ie. as a new process. You
can embed up to one instance of the formatting sequence "%s" in the
command: this will be substituted with the name of the public screen
that the menu is attached to. This can be very useful if the program
accepts a public screen argument, eg. "MultiView PUBSCREEN %s".@{par}

@{b}KEY/K@{ub}@{line}
Optionally, specify a menu shortcut key for this item.@{par}

@{b}ST=STACK/K/N@{ub}@{line}
Optionally, specify a stack size in bytes for the program. If omitted,
the program inherits ScreenBacker's stack size.@{par}

@{b}PRI=PRIORITY/K/N@{ub}@{line}
Optionally, specify a task priority for the program. If omitted,
defaults to 0.@{par}

@{b}OP=OUTPUT/K@{ub}@{line}
Optionally, specify a standard output for the program. You can embed
one instance of the formatting sequence "%s" in this, which will be
substituted with the name of the public screen that the menu is
attached to. This can be very useful in conjunction with the SCREEN
specifier of console windows. If omitted, the output defaults to:
"CON:20/20/600/100/ScreenBacker Output/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT/SCREEN %s".@{par}

@{b}CD=CURDIR/K@{ub}@{line}
Optionally, specify the current directory for the program. If omitted,
the program inherits ScreenBacker's current directory.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

